---
import BaseLayout from "../layouts/BaseLayout.astro";
---

<BaseLayout
  title="Status: real uptime, real incidents, no dashboards"
  description="letmepost.dev API, OAuth, webhooks, and per-platform upstream health. The same numbers we look at."
>
  <header class="wrap page-head">
    <p class="crumb"><a href="/">letmepost</a> / status</p>
    <p class="eyebrow">Status</p>
    <h1 class="cl-h1" style="max-width: 16ch;">The same numbers we look at.</h1>
    <p class="sub" style="max-width: 58ch;">
      Status is whatever the metrics say. No green-coloured pixels papering over a
      degraded fan-out. When an upstream platform's OAuth flakes, this page calls it.
    </p>
  </header>

  <section class="wrap sec tight" style="padding-top: 28px;">
    <div class="callout">
      <span class="callout-tag">Operational</span>
      <p>
        <b>All systems operational.</b> Pre-launch. Real uptime and incident history
        surface here once the API takes production traffic.
      </p>
    </div>

    <div class="prose" style="margin-top: 32px;">
      <h2>Monitored surfaces</h2>
      <ul>
        <li>API gateway (<code>api.letmepost.dev</code>)</li>
        <li>OAuth connect flows per platform</li>
        <li>Webhook delivery pipeline</li>
        <li>Background publishing workers</li>
        <li>Per-platform upstream health (Bluesky, LinkedIn, X, Meta, …)</li>
      </ul>

      <h2>Subscribing</h2>
      <p>
        Once the status endpoints are wired, you'll be able to subscribe via RSS, email,
        or a webhook. Until then,
        <a href="https://github.com/rosekamallove/letmepost.dev" rel="noopener" target="_blank">the GitHub repo</a>
        is the source of truth.
      </p>
    </div>
  </section>
</BaseLayout>
